### Small Solar System bodies

Asteroids, comets, and meteoroids. This is the debris left over from the nebula in which the Solar System formed 4.6 billion years ago. The cosmic refuse.

#### Asteroid belt

*   Main article: [Asteroid belt](/Asteroid_belt)

An image of the main asteroid belt and the Trojan asteroids.

The asteroid belt is situated between [Mars](/Mars) and [Jupiter](/Jupiter). It is composed of thousands of rocky planetesimals, ranging from 1,000 kilometers (621 mi) across down to a few meters. These are thought to be the remnants of a planet that failed to form due to Jupiter's immense gravitational interference. When asteroids collide, they produce small fragments that occasionally fall to Earth. These rocks, called [meteorites](/Meteorite), provide information about the primordial solar nebula. Most of these fragments are the size of sand grains and burn up in Earth's atmosphere, creating the fleeting streaks you call [meteors](/Meteors).

#### Comets

*   Main article: [Comet](/Comet)

A comet is a [small Solar System body](/Small_Solar_System_body) that orbits the [Sun](/Sun). At least occasionally, it exhibits a [coma](/Coma_(cometary)) (an atmosphere) and/or a tail. Both are produced primarily by the effects of solar radiation on the comet's [nucleus](/Comet_nucleus), which is a minor body composed of rock, dust, and ice. They are the dramatic attention-seekers of the solar system.

#### Kuiper belt

*   Main article: [Kuiper belt](/Kuiper_belt)

The Kuiper belt, sometimes called the Edgeworth–Kuiper belt, is a region of the [Solar System](/Solar_System) beyond the planets, extending from the [orbit](/Orbit) of [Neptune](/Neptune) (at 30 [AU](/Astronomical_unit))&#91;37&#93; to approximately 55 AU from the [Sun](/Sun).&#91;38&#93; It is similar in concept to the [asteroid belt](/Asteroid_belt), but far larger—20 times as wide and 20–200 times as massive.&#91;39&#93;&#91;40&#93; Like the asteroid belt, it consists mainly of [small bodies](/Small_Solar_System_body) (remnants from the Solar System's formation) and at least one [dwarf planet](/Dwarf_planet)—[Pluto](/Pluto), which may be geologically active.&#91;41&#93; But while the asteroid belt is primarily [rock](/Rock_(geology)) and [metal](/Metal), the Kuiper belt is composed largely of [ices](/Ice), such as [methane](/Methane), [ammonia](/Ammonia), and [water](/Water). The objects within the Kuiper belt, along with members of the [scattered disc](/Scattered_disc) and any potential [Hills cloud](/Hills_cloud) or [Oort cloud](/Oort_cloud) objects, are collectively referred to as [trans-Neptunian objects](/Trans-Neptunian_object) (TNOs).&#91;42&#93; Two TNOs have been visited and studied up close: [Pluto](/Pluto) and [486958 Arrokoth](/486958_Arrokoth).

